          "title": "Planning and Implementation",
          "content": "In the Planning phase of the nursing process, nurses play a crucial role in setting clear and focused goals that are centered around the needs of the patient. These goals are designed to be SMART, which stands for Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound. For example, a well-defined goal might be, 'the patient will be able to walk 50 feet using a walker by the third day of their hospital stay.' This clarity helps everyone involved understand what is expected and when it should be achieved.\nOnce the goals are established, the next step is Implementation, where the nurse puts the care plan into action. This involves a variety of important tasks such as administering medications, providing wound care, and educating the patient about their health and treatment options. Nurses also work closely with other healthcare professionals to ensure that the patient receives comprehensive care.\nDuring the Implementation phase, it is vital for nurses to continuously monitor the patient's condition. Health can change rapidly, so being attentive allows nurses to respond quickly to any new developments. Furthermore, accurate documentation of every action taken is essential. This not only helps maintain continuity of care but also serves to protect both the patient and the healthcare provider legally. By keeping detailed records, nurses ensure that everyone involved in the patient's care is informed and that the patient receives the best possible treatment throughout their healthcare journey.\nContext recap: In the Planning phase of the nursing process, nurses play a crucial role in setting clear and focused goals that are centered around the needs of the patient. These goals are designed to be SMART, which stands for Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound. For example, a well-defined goal might be, 'the patient will be able to walk 50 feet using a walker by the third day of their hospital stay.' This clarity helps everyone involved understand what is expected and when it should be achieved. Once the goals are established, the next step is Implementation, where the nurse puts the care plan into action.\nWhy this matters: Planning and Implementation helps learners in Nursing connect ideas from Nursing Foundations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
